To tell truth, indeed, we are grieved and vexed to see such good store wasted, so much leakage and let- ting slip (μὴ ποτε παραῤῥυῶμεν. N. Τ. Ep. ad. Hebr. We think that, when the mind has been once awakened to “ a sense of the power and beauty of the poetry, the oratory, the history, and the philosophy of the Hellenic race,’' it should be kept awake to these glories, if possible—and this possibility we are pre- pared to establish, in the case of all who deem the question one of interest to themselves.
